# Code Quality Standards

Linting, formatting, type checking, and security requirements.

## Hard Requirements

- Do: enforce linting, formatting, type checks, and tests before merge.
- Do: run security scans for backend dependencies and code.
- Do not: merge known failing lint/type checks without explicit waiver.
- Why: automated quality gates prevent regressions and reduce review overhead.

## Opinionated Defaults

- Backend: use a fast linter, formatter, dependency scanner, and type checks.
- Frontend: use linting, formatting, strict typing, and avoid `any`.
- Prefer pre-commit hooks for fast local feedback.
- CI/coverage expectations are canonicalized in `quality-gates.mdc`.

## Exceptions

- Legacy modules can use temporary ignore lists only with issue tracking and
  expiry date.
- Typed escape hatches (`any`, `# type: ignore`) are allowed only with
  justification comments.

## Acceptance Checks

- CI includes lint, format, type-check, and test stages.
- Branch protection blocks merges on failing required checks.
- New code avoids untracked lint/type suppressions.

## Examples

```python
# ✅ GOOD - Type hints
def create_task(week_id: int, title: str) -> Task:
    return Task.objects.create(week_id=week_id, title=title)
```

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Proper types
interface Task {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  isCompleted: boolean;
}

function updateTask(task: Task): Promise<Task> {
  // Implementation
}

// ❌ BAD - Using 'any'
function updateTask(task: any): any {
  // Implementation
}
```
